\boxed{6}
I found the derivative of the function $ f(n) = \frac{n}{2} + \frac{18}{n} $, which is $ f'(n) = \frac{1}{2} - \frac{18}{n^2} $. Setting this equal to zero gives $ \frac{1}{2} = \frac{18}{n^2} $, leading to $ n^2 = 36 $ and $ n = 6 $.

